{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
<h1>Middleware</h1>
<p>
    Middleware provides a convenient mechanism for filtering HTTP requests entering your application.
    It sits between the request and the controller, allowing you to inspect, modify, or block requests.
</p>

<h2>Creating Middleware</h2>
<p>
    Use the CLI command to generate a new middleware:
</p>
<pre><code class="language-bash">php rhapsody make:middleware CheckIfAdmin</code></pre>
<p>
    This creates a new middleware class in <code>app/Middleware/</code>.
</p>

<h2>Middleware Structure</h2>
<p>
    All middleware must extend <code>Rhapsody\Core\Middleware\Middleware</code> and implement the <code>handle()</code> method:
</p>
<pre><code class="language-php">namespace App\Middleware;

use Rhapsody\Core\Middleware\Middleware;
use Rhapsody\Core\Request;
use Rhapsody\Core\Response;
use Rhapsody\Core\Routing\Route;

class CheckIfAdmin extends Middleware
{
    public function handle(Request $request, ?Route $route = null): ?Response
    {
        // Check if user is admin
        if (!Session::get('is_admin')) {
            return redirect('/home');
        }
        
        // Return null to continue the request
        return null;
    }
}</code></pre>

<h2>Types of Middleware</h2>
<h3>Global Middleware</h3>
<p>
    Global middleware runs on every matched request. Configure them in <code>config.php</code>:
</p>
<pre><code class="language-php">'global' => [
    \Rhapsody\Core\Middleware\VerifyCsrfTokenMiddleware::class,
    \Rhapsody\Core\Middleware\DdosMiddleware::class,
],</code></pre>

<h3>Route-Specific Middleware</h3>
<p>
    Apply middleware to specific routes by chaining the <code>middleware()</code> method:
</p>
<pre><code class="language-php">Router::get('/dashboard', [DashboardController::class, 'index'])
    ->middleware('auth');
    
Router::get('/admin', [AdminController::class, 'index'])
    ->middleware('auth', 'admin');</code></pre>

<h2>Built-in Middleware</h2>
<ul>
    <li><code>AuthMiddleware</code> – Redirects unauthenticated users to the login page.</li>
    <li><code>GuestMiddleware</code> – Redirects authenticated users away from guest-only pages.</li>
    <li><code>VerifyCsrfTokenMiddleware</code> – Validates CSRF tokens on POST requests.</li>
    <li><code>DdosMiddleware</code> – Protects against excessive requests using rate limiting.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Middleware Configuration</h2>
<p>
    Define the middleware map in <code>config.php</code>:
</p>
<pre><code class="language-php">'map' => [
    'auth'    => \Rhapsody\Core\Middleware\AuthMiddleware::class,
    'guest'   => \Rhapsody\Core\Middleware\GuestMiddleware::class,
    'admin'   => \App\Middleware\AdminMiddleware::class,
],</code></pre>

<h2>Middleware Execution Order</h2>
<ol>
    <li>All global middleware run in the order they are defined.</li>
    <li>Route-specific middleware run in the order they are chained.</li>
    <li>If any middleware returns a <code>Response</code>, the request is short-circuited.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Debugging Middleware</h2>
<p>
    The debug toolbar includes a <strong>Middleware</strong> panel that shows:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Which middleware were executed.</li>
    <li>Whether they were global or route-specific.</li>
    <li>Execution time for each middleware.</li>
</ul>
